CIRCUIT COURT OF
TALLAPOOSA COUNTY, ALABAMA
PATRICK CRADDOCK, CLERK
IN THE CIRCUIT COURT OF TALLAPOOSA COUNTY, ALABAMA
AT ALEXANDER CITY
CHRISTOPHER BLAINE MCGREGOR )
PLAINTIFF/RESPONDENT )
VS. ) CASE NO. DR-2023-900051.01
BRITTANY MICHELLE GILLILAND )
DEFENDANT/PETITIONER )
MOTION FOR CONTEMPT and
MOTION FOR TEMPORARY PENDENTE LITE ORDER
Comes now the Plaintiff/Respondent, Christopher Blaine McGregor, by and through his
attorney, Dianne James Davis, and files this Motion for Contempt and would state as follows:
1. That the Final Decree of Divorce entered by this Court on February 27, 2024, states
as follows: “If an appeal from this decree is taken within sixty (60) days, neither
party shall marry again except to each other during the pendency of said appeal.”
2. That in the Sunday, February 9, 2025, edition of The Clanton Advertiser published in
the Public Records section under Marriages, it reads as follows: January 31
Bradley Dale Cleckler to Brittany Michelle Gilliland, see Exhibit “A”.
3. That the Final Decree of Divorce contains the Alabama Relocation Act that states
“…you must give notice by certified mail of the proposed change of principal
residence on or before the 45th day before a proposed change of principal
residence. If you do not know and cannot reasonably become aware of such
information in sufficient time to provide a 45-day notice, you must give such
notice by certified mail not later than the 10th day after the date that you obtain
such information…”
4. That the Father has reason to believe that the Mother has moved to Clanton, Alabama,
which is approximately one and one-half hours away from her former residence in
Alexander City, Alabama, and as of the date of this filing, has failed to notify the
father of her current living address. Attached is a copy of the Alabama Marriage
DOCUMENT 163
Certificate of the Defendant/Petitioner and her new husband showing her “Residence
County” is Chilton County – EXHIBIT B.
5. That the Final Decree of Divorce states regarding visitation: The Wife shall have
visitation periods as follows: From picking up the children on Thursday at school
until taking the children back to school on the following Monday morning on the
1st and 3rd weeks of each month.”
6. That the minor child, namely: B.M., dob, 05/10/2019, is five (5) years old and the one
(1) eighteen (18 ) minute drive from Alexander City to Clanton on Thursday night
and then the one (1) hour eighteen (18) minute drive back to Alexander City Friday
morning and Monday morning for school is exhausting for the young minor child.
7. That since the Mother is now employed in Clanton and does not get off until 6:00pm,
her father is picking the minor child up from after the bell by 5:30 and returns to his
home in Dadeville on Thursday and Friday. The Mother drives from Clanton (Credit
Central, 1107 7th Street S., Clanton) to Dadeville to pick up the minor child before
driving to 334 Co Rd 43, Clanton which is a two (2) hour twenty-one (21) minute
round trip drive for the mother and one (1) hour ten (10) minute ride for the minor
child at approximately 7:15 pm at night which would put him getting to his Mother’s
home in Clanton at approximately 8:25 pm. That the minor child’s bed time is
approximately 8:30 pm at his Father’s home.
8. That the Alabama Relocation Act states: If there is to be a change of principal
residence by you or by a child subject to the custody or visitation provisions’ of this
order, you must provide the following information to each other person who has
custody or visitation rights under this decree as follows: (7) A proposal for revised
schedule of custody of or visitation with a child”.
9. That on February 9, 2025, the Father sent a text to the mother asking that they “get
together & work something out that will align with you living & working out of
AC to make sure Bennett stays in AC on school night. You promised that you
would stay in AC on school nights.” Copy of text attached as Exhibit “C”. That
the mother has not been receptive to this text.
10. That the Final Decree of Divorce is on appeal; however, the Father feels that a
temporary order to amend visitation pendente lite for the minor child to visit with the
DOCUMENT 163
Mother from Friday after school until Sunday evening at 7:00 pm. would be
beneficial to keep the minor child from traveling such a distance on the Thursday
night, Friday morning and Monday morning of visitation.
WHEREFORE the premises considered, the Father request this Court find the Mother in
contempt of court for:
a. Failure to abide by the Final Decree of Divorce by marrying someone other
than the Father during the pendency of said appeal;
b. Failure to abide by the Alabama Relocation Act;
That further, the premises considered, the Father requests this Court enter a temporary order
pendente lite to amend the minor child’s visitation due to the travel time involved now that the Mother
has moved one (1) hour and eighteen (18) minutes from the minor child.
Respectfully submitted on this the day of February, 2025.
/s/Dianne James Davis
